    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No worries at all! The \"ritual\" part was just a metaphor for how many moving parts are involved, but you're right, we can skip the cult stuff and get straight to the mechanics. You don't need to join a cult to buy a condo in Toronto; you just need to understand that the money is held in a specialized account called an **Escrow Account** (often managed by a title company or a lawyer in Ontario) until the deal is officially closed.\n\nHere is the actual step-by-step flow of your money, with a little extra context on why the process is so structured:\n\n1.  **Funding the Escrow:** Once your offer is accepted, you don't just wire the money directly to the seller. Instead, you instruct your lender (if you're getting a mortgage) or your own bank to transfer the funds to the Escrow Account. In Toronto, this usually happens via a **wire transfer** to ensure it's secure and traceable. The Escrow Officer then sends a confirmation to your lender that the funds have arrived.\n2.  **The \"Clear to Close\" Check:** Before the money is released, the Escrow Officer (or your lawyer) runs a final check",
